I"ç<h1 id="overview">Overview</h1>
<p><a href="https://www.apple.com/airtag/">Apple AirTags</a> are small Bluetooth Low Energy tracking devices that can fit in a pocket or wallet. While AirTags are intended to be used to find misplaced and lost items, they also provide a cheap and incredibly effective way to track someone without their consent. AirTags use Appleâ€™s <a href="https://www.howtogeek.com/725842/what-is-apples-find-my-network/">Find My Network</a>, enabled by default on Apple products like iPhones, iPads, and Mac computers, to update the network as to the deviceâ€™s current location. However, unlike previous devices such as <a href="https://www.thetileapp.com/en-us/">Tile</a>, which had sporadic coverage even in urban areas, the widespread coverage of the Find My Network (i.e. any Apple device that has not actively opted out), means that these devices are perfect tools for <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2022/02/11/technology/airtags-gps-surveillance.html">stalking</a>.</p>
